{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 2.3.4 Die Rolls\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To determine how well you use an ability, roll a 20-sided die (d20). At the same time, your GM rolls for the resistance.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Compare your rolled number with the TN to determine the level of success or failure for the roll (not the contest as a whole).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Critical: If the die roll is 1 (even when the TN is 1), you succeed so brilliantly that your GM may reward them with an extra, unexpected effect.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Success: If the die roll is greater than 1 and less than or equal to the TN, you succeed, but there is nothing remarkable about the success.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Failure: If the die roll is greater than the TN but not 20, you fail. Things do not happen as hoped.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Fumble: If the die roll is 20, you fumble (even when the TN is 20). This is the worst result possible, and you will suffer a disturbing or entertaining catastrophe.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 2.3.5 Victory or Defeat\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your roll\u8217's degree of success or failure and that of your GM\u8217's roll are compared to determine your overall victory or defeat for the contest as a whole.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If you have a better result than the GM, then you have a victory and you gain the prize set out when the contest was framed.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If you have a worse result, then you are defeated and do not gain the prize.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If you both have the same level success or failure, the better roll wins.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 if your rolls tie, then it is a standoff.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your GM describes what happens, based on their interpretation of the results.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 2.3.5.1 Better Roll\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 QuestWorlds supports two options for the \u8220"better roll\u8221": the highest roll, or the lowest roll. Some groups prefer lowest roll, some higher. The preference toward \u8220"low is better\u8221", is often because because 1 is a critical and 20 a fumble, and toward \u8220"high is better\u8221" because the winner has rolled a higher number. Groups wanting higher abilities to win out slightly more often should use higher roll.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We also use the phrase "worse roll@ to indicate the losing roll.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 2.3.5.2 Confusing Ties\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your GM will describe most tied results as inconclusive standoffs, in which neither of you gets what you wanted.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In some situations, ties become difficult to visualize. Chief among these are contests with binary outcomes, where only two possible results are conceivable.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your GM can either change the situation on such a tie, introducing a new element that likely renders the original prize irrelevant to both participants, or they can resolve the ties in your favor.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 2.3.5.3 Bumps\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A bump affects the degree of success or failure of your die roll. A bump up improves your result by one step, changing a fumble to a failure, a failure to a success, or a success to a critical. Bump ups come from two sources: masteries and hero points (applied in that order). A bump down reduces the degree of success of your opponent. Bump downs come from one source: masteries.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 2.3.5.4 Bump Up with Mastery\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If you\u8217're engaged in a contest against a resistance, and you have an ability of 10M versus a resistance of 10, you enjoy an advantage. You get a bump to your die roll from that mastery.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You get one bump up for each level of mastery your PC has greater than your opponent\u8217's. So against a resistance of 14 a PC\u8217's ability of 7M is treated as 7 vs.\u160?14 but we bump the result one step in the the favor of the PC; a PC\u8217's ability of 3M2 is treated as 3 vs.\u160?14 but we bump the result two steps in the the favor of the the PC.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This reflects the fact that an ability above 20 would always succeed on a D20. Because each mastery represents automatic success (apart from a fumble) on a D20, you roll against the remainder, and treat the mastery as a bump. So on an ability of 27 is 7M, which means a target number of 7 and bump the result; an ability of 43 means 3M2 or a target number of 3 and bump the result twice.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Opposed masteries cancel out, each contestant reducing their rating by the same number of masteries until only one or neither of them has masteries. If you have two masteries, then you enjoy the same great advantage over an opponent with a single mastery as a someone with one mastery has over an opponent with no masteries. If you have an advantage of two or more masteries over an opponent, you can pretty much count on pounding him into the dust.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This allows QuestWorlds to represent large differences in ability or resistance.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 2.3.5.5 Bump Up with Hero Points\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You can spend a hero point to bump up any result by one step. You may only bump your own rolls, not those of other PCs or supporting characters\u8212-with the exception of sidekicks and retainers, which, as extensions of your character, you may spend hero points on. You can decide to use a hero point for a bump after the die roll results are calculated (including any bump ups resulting from masteries).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You can only spend one hero point per roll.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 2.4 Augments\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You may sometimes face contests where more than one ability may be applicable to the conflict at hand. In such cases, you may attempt to use one ability to give a supporting bonus to the main ability you are using to frame the contest. This is called an Augment. For example, if your character has the abilities \u8220"The Queen\u8217's Intelligencer\u8221" and \u8220"Master of Disguise\u8221", you might use the latter to augment the former when infiltrating a rival nation\u8217's capitol. Similarly, a character with \u8220"Knight Errant\u8221" and \u8220"My Word is my Bond\u8221" abilities might use one to augment the other when in conflict with an obstacle the character has sworn to overcome.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Abilities that represent special items, weapons, armor, or other noteworthy equipment can be a common source of augments. However, this grows tired if over-used and you should try and restrict repeated use equipment used in this way to contests where they are particularly interesting or apropos.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Augments can also come from other characters abilities if one character uses an ability to support another\u8217's efforts rather than directly engaging in the contest. Augments can even come from outside resources like support from a community or other circumstantial help.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If you have a good idea for an augment, propose it to your GM while the contest is being framed. When making your proposal, describe how the augmenting ability supports the main one in a way that is both {\b entertaining} and {\b memorable}. Don\u8217't just hunt for mechanical advantage, show your group more about your PC when you augment, their attitudes, passions, or lesser known abilities. If you are augmenting with a broad ability like \u8220"Fool\u8217's Luck\u8221", be prepared to describe the unlikely events that tilt the scales in your favor. Your GM will decide whether the augment is justified and can refuse boring and uninspired attempts to augment, where you are just looking for a bonus to your roll and not adding to the story.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You may only use one of your own abilities to augment the ability you are using in the contest, and you may not use an ability to augment itself. However, augments from other players supporting you can add together with your own, along with other modifiers, including those from benefits of victory and from plot augments.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If you GM accepts your augment proposal, it will a be resolved by one of the methods below. The main contest then proceedes as normal, with any bonus from the augment added onto the rating of the ability chosen when framing the contest. The augment remains in effect for the duration of the contest.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 2.4.1 Rolled Augments\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To grant an augment to yourself, or another PC, in an upcoming contest, you engage in a simple contest against a Moderate resistance before the main contest begins to determine whether the augment attempt results in and advantage. Frame this augment contest with your GM, making it clear how your supporting ability will achieve the goal of making your ability in the main contest more effective. Augment contests may not themselves be augmented, and if your augment attempt results in defeat, you may not make another attempt at an augment for the main contest.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If you are victorious in the augment contest, your GM will award a bonus of +3 to the ability used in the the main contest. If your description of how you were using the augmenting ability was particularly entertaining, your GM may increase the bonus to +6.\par}
